hacking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:7;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"passwords\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:8;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"tweets\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:9;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"twerrorism\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:10;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"twerrorist\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"http://theseedstudio.com/?p=468\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:395:\"As Twitter becomes more ubiquitous in the business and personal communication landscape it&#8217;s almost inevitable that some unscrupulous individuals (or perhaps even organizations) will try to subvert this service for their own gain. Lately we&#8217;ve heard from a few clients&#8230; <a\nhref=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/09/19/counter-twerrorism/\" class=\"read_more\">Read the rest</a>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Evan Aagaard\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6732:\"<p><a\nhref=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/09/19/counter-twerrorism/twitter-problems/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-470\"><img\nclass=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-470\" title=\"Twitter-Problems\" src=\"http://theseednetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/Twitter-Problems.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"540\" height=\"195\" /></a></p><p>As Twitter becomes more ubiquitous in the business and personal communication landscape it&#8217;s almost inevitable that some unscrupulous individuals (or perhaps even organizations) will try to subvert this service for their own gain. Lately we&#8217;ve heard from a few clients who have had their twitter accounts essentially hijacked with false tweets posted by someone other than them and when you&#8217;re using twitter as one of your avenues for building trust and dialogue with your customers this can be a very scary situation indeed.</p><p>This is unfortunately the evolution of spamming, or in other words spamming has now gone social. As the internet has become more secure the bad guys have started to play dirtier and Twitter hacking is on the rise, often with some very high profile sneak attacks as when the NBC News twitter account was <a\nhref=\"http://news.cnet.com/8301-27080_3-20104165-245/nbc-news-twitter-account-hacked/\">hijacked</a> by the Hacker group Script Kiddies days before the recent 9/11 anniversary.</p><p>So what should you do if you think your twitter has been compromised and suddenly you&#8217;re @You account is spewing out links to Chinese herbal sex pills and free iPad 2&#8242;s?</p><p>First, don&#8217;t panic- twitter is aware of the problem and they&#8217;ve got a support process for just this very scenario. There are essentially two scenarios you might encounter 1) Your account has been hijacked with rogue tweets but you still have access to it or 2) your account has been hijacked and you&#8217;ve been locked out because the &#8220;Twerrorist&#8221; has changed your password.</p><p>First, let&#8217;s look at the steps to take if you still have access to your account.</p><p><strong>1. Change your password</strong></p><p>If you still have access to your account (i.e. the sinister party in question has not locked you out of it by changing the password) then change the password immediately in the <a\nhref=\"https://twitter.com/account/password\">Passwords tab</a>in your Account Settings. You&#8217;re best advised to choose a strong password that contains both letters, numbers and even symbols.</p><p><strong>2. Revoke Connections</strong></p><p><a\nhref=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/09/19/counter-twerrorism/screen-shot-2011-09-19-at-3-18-00-pm/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-478\"><img\nclass=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-478\" title=\"Screen shot 2011-09-19 at 3.18.00 PM\" src=\"http://theseednetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/Screen-shot-2011-09-19-at-3.18.00-PM-300x206.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"206\" /></a>This is where people often get into trouble, there are now so many ways to link our twitter accounts to other online services that we can easily loose track of what services and applications we&#8217;ve granted access to and this is &#8220;the backdoor&#8221; that hackers often use to gain access to our accounts. While logged into your twitter account visit the <a\nhref=\"http://twitter.com/settings/applications\">applications tab</a>in the Account Settings and review which third-party applications have access to your account and revoke any you don&#8217;t recognize.</p><p><strong>3. Update your new password in your trusted applications</strong></p><p><strong></strong>Of course many of us use trusted third-party applications/services (i.e. Hootsuite, Tweetdeck etc) with our twitter accounts so be sure to update your new twitter password with those applications. Otherwise you may be locked out of your account when those applications make too many failed login attempts.</p><p>If your account has been compromised Twitter also recommends taking these additional precautions:</p><ul><li>Delete any unwanted Tweets that were posted while your account was compromised.</li><li>Scan your computers for viruses and malware, especially if unauthorized accountbehaviorscontinue to be posted after you&#8217;ve changed the password.</li><li>Install security patches for your operating system and applications</li><li>Always use a strong, new password you don&#8217;t use elsewhere and would be difficult to guess.</li><li>Visit the<a\ntitle=\"Safe Tweeting Help Page\" href=\"https://support.twitter.com/articles/76036-safety-keeping-your-account-secure\">Safe Tweeting page</a>for more information on avoiding hacks and phishing.</li></ul><div>If your account has been hijacked and you&#8217;ve been locked out (a far morefrustratingscenario) then try following these steps:</div><div><h3>1. Request a password reset</h3><p><a\nhref=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/09/19/counter-twerrorism/screen-shot-2011-09-19-at-3-27-29-pm/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-481\"><img\nclass=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-481\" title=\"Screen shot 2011-09-19 at 3.27.29 PM\" src=\"http://theseednetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/Screen-shot-2011-09-19-at-3.27.29-PM-150x141.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"141\" /></a>Reset your password by requesting an email from this<a\ntitle=\"password reset form\" href=\"http://twitter.com/account/resend_password\">password reset form.</a>Try entering both your username and email address, and be sure to check for the email in any email accounts that you might have used on your Twitter account.</p><p>If youre able to log in after the password reset, please re-secure your account by following the above steps.</p><h3>2. Contact support if you still require assistance</h3><p>If you still can&#8217;t log in, contact Twitter by submitting a<a\nhref=\"https://support.twitter.com/forms/general\">Support request</a>.<strong>Please choose &#8220;Hacked or phished account&#8221; as the subject of your request.</strong>Be sure to use the email address you associated with the hacked Twitter account; Twitter will then send additional information and instructions to that email address. Include both your username and the date you last had access to your account.</p><p>And if the If youve lost access to the actual email account associated with your Twitter account, try this<a\ntitle=\"help page\" href=\"https://support.twitter.com/articles/107907-i-don-t-have-access-to-my-account-s-email-address-anymore\">help page</a>.</p><p>Last but not least don&#8217;t dismay! Here at The Seed we&#8217;re always ready to help so if you have further connections and would like to speak with a Counter-Twerrorism expert give us a call or drop us an email. We&#8217;ll get ya sorted out.</p></div><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p> \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/09/19/counter-twerrorism/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:42:\"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0\";a:1:{s:8:\"origLink\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/09/19/counter-twerrorism/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"                \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:6:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"Content Marketing: the W5 Strategy\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/ai1ec/~3/rSStBlIJlvY/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/06/17/content-marketing/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 17 Jun 2011 22:01:04 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:8:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Blogging\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"Content Development\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"Networks & Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3:\"SEO\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"calendar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"content\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:6;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"content marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:7;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"stats\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"http://theseedstudio.com/?p=318\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:348:\"You may have heard that when it comes to online marketing, content is king. 87% of all businesses are engaged in some form of <strong>content marketing&#8230; <a\nhref=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/06/17/content-marketing/\" class=\"read_more\">Read the rest</a></strong>. There are 3 good reasons for this.First, people trust blog posts, videos\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Dan Logtenberg\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4467:\"<p>You may have heard that when it comes to online marketing, content is king. <a\ntitle=\"Content Marketing Report\" href=\"http://www.contentmarketinginstitute.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/B2B-Content-Marketing-2010-Small-Organization-Report.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">87% of all businesses</a> are engaged in some form of <strong>content marketing</strong>. There are 3 good reasons for this.</p><p><a\nhref=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/06/17/content-marketing/content/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-320\"><img\nclass=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-320\" title=\"content\" src=\"http://theseednetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/content.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a></p><p>First, people trust blog posts, videos and reviews more than they trust advertising. 60-70% of users are more likely to buy something after reading a post or watching a video about it than after seeing an ad.</p><p>Second, content marketing is essential to improving search engine ranking. Every post you create gets indexed by Google, Bing and others, increasing your exposure for that topic and improving your website&#8217;s overall search ranking. Ads, on the other hand are essentially invisible to search engines and have no long term impact on search ranking at all.</p><p>And third, in most cases, content marketing is also less expensive than advertising.</p><h2>First, the Hard Part.</h2><p>So, if content marketing has more impact AND is cheaper, why isn&#8217;t everyone doing it?</p><p>For most people, content is a lot harder to create than an ad.You might be great at running your business and passionate about what you do, but if you&#8217;re like a lot of entrepreneurs, you clam up when you try to write it down. Creating interesting and original content takes time, and most entrepreneurs aren&#8217;t natural writers.</p><h2>The W5 Content Solution</h2><p>The easiest and arguably best way to create content is simply to answer one or more of these questions:<strong>&#8220;Who?&#8221;</strong>,<strong>&#8220;What?&#8221;</strong>,<strong>&#8220;When?&#8221;</strong>,<strong>&#8220;Where?&#8221;</strong>,<strong>&#8220;Why?&#8221;</strong> or<strong>&#8220;How?&#8221;</strong></p><p>There are probably thousands of W questions related to your business that you can answer right now. If you&#8217;re still stuck, think about the questions your customers ask every day about your products or services.</p><h3>The Forumla:</h3><p>Here&#8217;s a formula for creating content that works for me:</p><ol><li>Every time someone asks me a question about our services, company or industry, I write it down. I also pay attention to the answer I give and any follow-up questions and I write them down too.</li><li>I make a bulleted list of my answer, trying to make it as simple and clear as possible.</li><li>I write down where the question comes from. I might explain the story of the customer or I might give some broader context. For example, do a lot of other people have the same question? If so, why? What does this say about my industry or service that so many people are puzzled by the same thing?</li><li>When it comes time to post to your blog, all you need to do is rewrite your notes as simply and as clearly as possible.</li><li>You may want to start with an anecdote or fact to better explain why the question matters and examples of how the answer can be used.</li><li>Format you post: reference your statements and list your sources where possible, date your work and use sub-titles. Your readers and Google will love you for it!</li></ol><p>Again, keep it simple but also keep it personal. Your readers are more likely to trust you if you sound genuine.</p><p>Have you tried content marketing? What worked for you?</p><ul><li>Here are more <a\nhref=\"http://www.bazaarvoice.com/resources/stats\" target=\"_blank\">stats on content and social media marketing</a>.</li><li><a\ntitle=\"Copy Blogger\" href=\"http://copyblogger.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Copyblogger</a> has some great tips on <a\ntitle=\"Content Marketing and Copywriting\" href=\"http://www.copyblogger.com/content-marketing-copywriting/\">content marketing</a>.</li><li>Remember, everything starts with a good <a\ntitle=\"Online Marketing Strategy\" href=\"http://theseedstudio.com/services/strategy-planning/\">marketing strategy</a></li><li>Talk to us about our <a\ntitle=\"Internet Marketing Services\" href=\"http://theseedstudio.com/services/internet-marketing/\">Internet marketing services</a></li></ul> \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:65:\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/06/17/content-marketing/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:42:\"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0\";a:1:{s:8:\"origLink\";a:1:{i:0;a:5